Title:
Fixing Mimikatz sekurlsa::logonpasswords on Windows 11 24H2/25H2

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4ŌĆō8 sentences max):
- This post explains why stock Mimikatz `sekurlsa::logonpasswords` fails on Windows 11 24H2/25H2 (builds 26100/26200) with ŌĆ£Logon listŌĆØ and/or blank output, and how to patch it.  
- The root causes are (1) missing lsasrv.dll byte signatures for the new build, (2) a compiler change from RIP-relative to base-relative addressing when referencing `LogonSessionList`, and (3) internal structure layout changes that shift session and credential field offsets.  
- It walks through deriving new patterns, validating symbol addresses in WinDbg, and debugging Mimikatz by adding diagnostic prints to pinpoint where `ReadProcessMemory` fails due to an out-of-module resolved pointer.  
- Two fixes are proposed: adjust the address resolution formula to handle base-relative displacement (`module_base + disp`) or switch to an alternate signature in a function that still uses RIP-relative addressing.  
- Finally, it updates the MSV logon session and primary credential struct helpers to correct username/domain parsing and NTLM hash extraction.  
- Useful for red teamers and tool developers maintaining LSASS credential extraction tooling across Windows build changes; also relevant to defenders for understanding how signature-based LSASS scraping adapts to OS/compiler shifts.

Technical Focus:
- Mimikatz lsasrv.dll signature/pattern scanning (LsaSrvReferences[])
- RIP-relative vs base-relative addressing in x64 (`lea [rip+disp]` vs `lea [reg+disp]`)
- LSASS memory reading and pointer resolution (`ReadProcessMemory`, module base/size)
- Windows logon session enumeration (`LogonSessionList`, `LogonSessionListCount`)
- Internal struct/offset drift (KIWI_MSV1_0_LIST_* and MSV1_0_PRIMARY_CREDENTIAL_*)
- WinDbg-assisted reverse engineering and validation

Use Cases:
- Updating Mimikatz forks to support Windows 11 24H2/25H2 credential extraction
- Building resilient signature strategies for locating LSASS globals across builds
- Troubleshooting ŌĆ£Logon listŌĆØ / empty output issues in LSASS scrapers
- Researching how compiler/codegen changes break offensive tooling assumptions
- Creating detections around lsasrv.dll pattern scanning and LSASS enumeration behavior

Keywords:
Mimikatz, sekurlsa::logonpasswords, Windows 11 24H2, Windows 11 25H2, build 26100, build 26200, lsass.exe, lsasrv.dll, LogonSessionList, LogonSessionListCount, pattern scanning, byte signatures, RIP-relative addressing, base-relative addressing, LEA instruction, ReadProcessMemory, SeDebugPrivilege, WinDbg, MSV1_0_PRIMARY_CREDENTIAL, NTLM hash, KIWI_MSV1_0_LIST, struct offsets, Protected Process Light, RunAsPPL, Credential Guard, LsaIso.exe